# 09. Integration test for `{{ module_type }}/{{ module_name }}/{{ etl_name }}`

- [ ] In this github subissue, create a new branch to work on the issue
- [ ] Pull and checkout that branch in your local development environment.

While working on this checklist you may want to use VSCode to automatically open for editing the following files:

```bash
code tests/workflow/rules/{{ module_type }}/{{ module_name }}/test_snakemake_{{ etl_name }}.py
code data/tests/dry-run/<rule_name>.yaml
code workflow/rules/{{ module_type }}/{{ module_name }}/{{ etl_name }}.smk
```

The scaffolded integration test file provides the following:

- Uses the shared `workspace` fixture from `tests/workflow/rules/conftest.py`.
- Copies `data/tests/` into `workspace/data` via an autouse fixture.
- Calls `_snakemake(...)` against the generated aggregate rule target:
  `{{ module_type }}_{{ module_name }}_{{ etl_name }}_all`.
- Starts with `@pytest.mark.skip(...)` so generated projects do not fail before test data and assertions are implemented. **This should be removed when done with this to-do.

Consider implementing one of the following integration test approaches:

1) A simple dry run. Tell the snakemake command to run with the `--dry-run` argument. This will simply test that input data exists. For this pattern, create `data/tests/dry-run/<rule_name>.yaml`, then use `_load_touch_paths(...)` in the test fixture to create dummy input files in the temp test directory.

2) Test input file to output generation for a small test dataset. **This is the suggested approach**.

`data/tests/dry-run/all.yaml` is reserved for aggregate workflow targets (for example `dag_svg_all` and workflow-wide `all_data` dry runs).


- [ ] `tests/workflow/rules/{{ module_type }}/{{ module_name }}/test_snakemake_{{ etl_name }}.py`

  - [ ] Replace the placeholder skip marker after adding representative fixture data and assertions.
  - [ ] Decide whether this test should be `--dry-run` or a real execution.
  - [ ] Ensure the test target matches the ETL aggregate rule name: `{{ module_type }}_{{ module_name }}_{{ etl_name }}_all`.

## Test

### Lint and typecheck

- [ ] Lint and typecheck using `tox`.

  ```bash
  tox run-parallel --quiet -f py312 lint -f py312 typecheck
  ```

### Remote data tests

- [ ] Run tests that extract data from the remote source using the `remote_data` pytest marker. This will ensure that the methods works as expected with real data.

  ```bash
  tox run-parallel -e py312-workflow-rules -- --remote-data=any
  ```

### Full test suite

- [ ] Run the full `tox` test suite to ensure that all tests pass after the changes made in the previous steps.

  ```bash
  tox run-parallel
  ```
